  "prompt": "Is magnesium considered a solid, liquid or gas and why?",
  "response": "Magnesium is considered a solid at room temperature. It is a chemical element with the symbol Mg and atomic number 12. As a metal, magnesium has a defined structure in which its atoms are closely packed together in a crystalline lattice, giving it the characteristics typical of solid materials, such as a definite shape and volume.\n\nThe reason magnesium remains solid at room temperature is due to the strength of the metallic bonds between its atoms, which require a significant amount of energy to break. At higher temperatures, magnesium can melt (with a melting point of around 650 degrees Celsius or 1200 degrees Fahrenheit) and eventually vaporize (into a gas) at even higher temperatures. However, under standard conditions, magnesium is found in its solid state.",
